          <avActivityHighlights>The new snow and wind slabs represent the main danger.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>Above approximately 1600 m snow will fall until midday over a wide area. 20 to 30 cm of snow will fall above approximately 2200 m. &lt;br/&gt; Until the afternoon the weather will be partly cloudy. &lt;br/&gt; Small and medium-sized avalanches are possible as a consequence of the new snow. The new snow must be evaluated with care and prudence in all aspects and generally at intermediate and high altitudes.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>Towards its surface, the snowpack is weak. The new snow is bonding only slowly with the old snowpack in all aspects. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Below approximately 2400 m only a little snow is lying on south facing slopes.</snowpackStructureComment>
          <tendencyComment>Significant warming. &lt;br/&gt; On steep slopes numerous small and medium-sized gliding avalanches and moist snow slides are possible as the moisture increases.</tendencyComment>
